            <notesStmt>
                <note type="summary">
                    
                        
                            
                            <p>A letter from Sir Wilfrid Bliss Spender (1876-1960) to his wife, Lady Lillian Spender, n√©e Dean, (1880-1968). This letter is actually comprised of three separate sheets of paper, sent on the same date, but described by Spender as "scrawls" written in his spare time. Spender discusses financial matters, plans for his upcoming leave, and Lillian's current moves to secure a new house. He expresses frustration that he has received little news of his brother Rex.  In the second section of the letter, Spender suggests that as "Mab's children may be having a dull time, the Spenders' "Xmas gift" to them could be "an outing in town". He also notes that he has enclosed a cheque for three pounds. In the third section, Spender recounts a recent trip to the trenches, and mentions his gladness that Lillian has "hit it off so well with Lady C".</p>
                            
                        
                            
                        
                            
                            <p>Sir Wilfrid Spender was a member of the British Army until 1913 when controversy surrounding his signature of the Ulster Solemn League and Covenant resulted in his resignation. Spender was called up for military service in 1914 and from 1915 served in the 36th (Ulster) Division. Throughout the war, Spender wrote a collection of letters to his wife Lady Lillian Spender. The letters date mainly from 1915 to 1918, when Sir Wilfrid was serving in France. The letters concern politics, the Irish question, personal life, and Wilfrid's experience of the Great War.</p>
                            
                        
                    
                </note>
